```java
import java.util enums;

public class ResourceEditProperty {
    public static interface ResourceEditPropertyBuilder {

        void empty();
        
        ResourceEditPropertyBuilder withResource(String resourceType);
        
        ResourceEditPropertyBuilder withoutResource(String resourceType);
        ResourceEditPropertyBuilder withoutResource(Boolean isTesting);

        ResourceEditPropertyBuilder setIsTesting(boolean arg0) {
            this.isTesting = arg0;
            return this;
        }
    }

    static class Builder implements ResourceEditPropertyBuilder {

        private final Object resourceType;
        private final Object value;
        private final boolean isTesting;

        public Builder() {
            this(null, null, false);
        }

        public Builder(String resourceType) {
            this(resourceType, null, false);
        }

        public Builder(String resourceType, String value) {
            this(resourceType, value, false);
        }

        public Builder(String resourceType, Object value, boolean isTesting) {
            this.resourceType = resourceType;
            this.value = value;
            this.isTesting = isTesting;
        }

        @Override
        void empty() {
            setResourceType(null);
            setIsTesting(false);
        }

        @Override
        ResourceEditPropertyBuilder withResource(String resourceType) {
            return new Builder(resourceType, null, false);
        }

        @Override
        ResourceEditPropertyBuilder withoutResource(String resourceType) {
            return new Builder(null, null, false);
        }

        @Override
        ResourceEditPropertyBuilder withoutResource(Boolean isTesting) {
            return new Builder(null, null, isTesting);
        }

        @Override
        void setResourceType(String resourceType) {
            this.resourceType = resourceType;
        }

        @Override
        Object getValue() {
            return value;
        }
    }
}
```

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class StackOperations {
    public static void float(List<Object> elements) {
        if (elements.isEmpty()) {
            throw new EmptyStackException("The stack is empty");
        }
        
        // Remove the last element from the list
        elements.remove(elements.size() - 1);
    }

    /**
     * @param elements The stack to pop an element from.
     */
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Object> elements = new ArrayList<>();
        elements.add("a");
        elements.add("b");
        elements.add("c");

        try {
            float(elements); // This will remove "c"
            System.out.println(elements.contains("c")); // Prints: false
        } catch (EmptyStackException e) {
            System.out.println(e.getMessage()); // Prints the exception message if stack is empty
        }
    }
}
```

```java
    }
}
```

```java
    private PaintSurface paintSurface;
    private Surface surface;

    public PaintableSurface(int width, int height) {
        // Initialize the paint surface with given dimensions and properties
        if (surface != null && paintSurface != null)
            setSurfaceProperties(width, height);
        initialize();
    }

    @Override
    public void paintSurface() {
        // Perform drawing operation on the specified surface
        // Ensure resources are properly disposed after each draw call
        disposeResources();
    }

    private void initialize() {
        if (surface == null) {
            surface = new Surface(); // Assuming Surface is a valid implementation
        }

        // Initialize the paint surface with the current dimensions and properties
        setSurface(width, height);
    }

    private boolean hasSurface() {
        return surface != null;
    }

    public void setSurface(int width, int height) {
        if (surface == null)
            initialize();
        
        surface.setDimensions(width, height);

        // Update the paint surface with new dimensions
        paintSurface = new PaintSurface(width, height);
    }

    public void setSurfaceProperties(int width, int height) {
        if (surface == null)
            initialize();

        surface.setDimensions(width, height);

        // Update the paint surface with new dimensions
        paintSurface = new PaintSurface(width, height);
    }

    private void disposeResources() {
        if (surface != null && paintSurface != null) {
            Surface context = getGraphics();
            Graphics g = context.getGraphics();
            g.dispose(context);
            
            if (paintSurface != null)
                paintSurface.dispose();
        
            surface.dispose();
            surface = null;
        }
    }

    public void setSurface(Surface newSurface) {
        this.surface = newSurface;
    }

    @Override
    public Surface getSurface() {
        return surface;
    }

    // Event listener methods (assuming they are already handled)
}
```

```java
import org.apache.commons.math3.analysis.UnivariateRealFunction;
import org.apache.commonsmath3.solving.nongeneric BracketingAlgorithmImpl;
import org.apache.commonsmath3.solving.nongeneric UnivariateRealSolverUtils;

public class DoubleBracketExample {

    public static double[] bracket(UnivariateRealFunction arg0, double arg1, double arg2, double arg3) {
        // Create a solver using the bracketing algorithm
        final UnivariateRealSolverUtils solver = new UnivariateRealSolverUtils();
        
        // Use the default maximum number of iterations (Integer.MAX_VALUE)
        final double[] result = solver.solve(1, arg0, arg1, arg2, Double.NEGATIVE_INFINITY, Double.POSITIVE_INFINITY);
        
        if (result == null) {
            return null; // Or throw an exception if needed
        }
        
        return new double[]{result[0], result[1]};
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        UnivariateRealFunction f = x -> Math.cos(x); // Example function
        
        double[] interval = bracket(f, 0.0, Double.NaN, Double.NaN);
        if (interval != null) {
            System.out.println("Bracket found between: " + interval[0] + " and " + interval[1]);
        }
    }
}
```

```java
import java.time.DateTime;
import java.util.Date;

public class Example {

    public static DateTime getCurrentDate() {
        // Using java.time for modern Java (for better type safety and time zone handling)
        return LocalDateTime.now().-scalableToYear(1000).toDateTime();

    }
}
```

```java
import java.time.DateTime;
import java.time.ZonedDateTime;
import java.util.Date;

public class Example {

    public static DateTime getCurrentExactTime() {
        return LocalDateTime.now()
                .toPrecision(3600 * 1000) // 1 hour precision
                .scalableToYear(1000)
                .withTimeBands enabled();
    }

    public static DateTime getNowWithTimeZone(String timeZone) {
        try {
            ZonedDateTime now = ZonedDateTime.of("en-US", "2023-10-05T14:00:00").plusSeconds(5).toDateTime().ofZone(timeZone);
            return now;
        } catch (Exception e) {
            throw new RuntimeException(e);
        }
    }
}
```

Here's a Java implementation of an `int` function that returns a timeout value:

```java
// Method to calculate time difference in milliseconds (as int)
public static int calcTimeout(long startTime, long endTime) {
    // Calculate the difference between end and start times
    long diff = endTime - startTime;
    
    // Ensure non-negative result by adding one day if difference is negative
    if (diff < 0) {
        diff += 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000; // Add one day in milliseconds to make it positive
    }
    
    // Convert the difference to int and return it
    return (int) diff;
}

// Example usage:
public static void main(String[] args) {
    long startTime = System.currentTimeMillis();
    long endTime = startTime + 3600 * 1000; // Add one hour in milliseconds
    
    int timeout = calcTimeout(startTime, endTime);
    
    if (timeout > 0) {
        System.out.println("Time elapsed: " + timeout + " ms");
    } else {
        System.out.println("No time elapsed or end time is before start.");
    }
}
```

### Explanation:
- **Method Parameters:** The method takes two `long` parameters, `startTime` and `endTime`, representing the start and end times in milliseconds.
- **Timeout Calculation:** It calculates the difference between `endTime` and `startTime`. If this difference is negative (indicating that `endTime` is before `startTime`), it adds one day's worth of milliseconds to ensure a non-negative result.
- **Return Type:** The method returns an `int`, which represents the timeout in milliseconds. Note: Due to potential overflow when converting from `long` to `int`, this approach should be used carefully with large time differences.

### Example Usage:
In the provided example, we measure the elapsed time over a period of one hour (`3600 * 1000 = 3,600,000 ms`). The timeout value will reflect the actual elapsed milliseconds between `startTime` and `endTime`.

This implementation provides a simple and efficient way to calculate timeouts in Java applications.

```java
public class ExampleClass {
    private String variable;
    private int type;

    // Constructor with primitive types
    public ExampleClass(String name, int type) {
        this.variable = name;
        this.type = type;
    }

    // Constructor with objects
    public ExampleClass(Object name, Object type) {
        this(variable.toString(), (type != null) ? type.hashCode() : -1);
    }

    private String getVariableType() {
        if (this.type == 0) { // For primitive types, handle as default case
            throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Primitive types are not supported.");
        } else if (this.type == Integer.class.hashCode()) {
            return "integer";
        } else if (this.type == Double.class.hashCode()) {
            return "double";
        } else if (this.type == Boolean.class.hashCode()) {
            return "boolean";
        } else if (this.type == Character.class.hashCode()) {
            return "character";
        } else { // For other custom types
            return type.toString();
        }
    }

    public int computeHash() {
        String nameAndType = variable + ":" + getVariableType();
        int combinedHashCode = nameAndType.hashCode(); // Note: This won't work for Java versions <8 due to String.hashCode issues

        int declaringClassHashCode;
        try {
            declaringClassHashCode = this.getClass().hashCode();
        } catch (NoSuchMethodException e) {
            // If the class is not found, which shouldn't happen in normal operation
            // We can throw an exception or handle it gracefully
            throw new RuntimeException("Failed to compute declaring class hash code", e);
        }

        return declaringClassHashCode ^ combinedHashCode;
    }
}

        try {
            if (args.length >= 2) {

                // For primitive types, create a wrapper
                instance = new ExampleClass(variableName, type);
            } else if (args.length >= 3 && args[2] == "object") {
                Object name = args[1].getClass().nameForShort() + "(instance)";
                Object typeName = args[2].getClass().nameForShort();
                
                instance = new ExampleClass(name, typeName);
            }
        } catch (NumberFormatException e) {
            System.out.println("Invalid input format: " + e.getMessage());
        }

        if (instance != null) {
            int combinedHash = computeCombinedHash(instance.getName(), instance.getType());
            int declaringClassHash = exampleClass.hashCode();
            int finalHash = declaringClassHash ^ combinedHash;

            System.out.println("Final hash value: " + finalHash);
        } else {
            System.out.println("No valid class instance provided.");
        }
    }
}
```

Here is the Java equivalent of the provided C function:

```java
void function(float[] arg0, float[] arg1) {
    // Clamp values between 0 and 1 using max(0f, min(1f, value))
    float loc0 = Math.max(0f, Math.min(1f, arg0[0]));
    float loc1 = Math.max(0f, Math.min(1f, arg0[1]));
    float loc2 = Math.max(0f, Math.min(1f, arg0[2]));
    
    // Compute the weighted sum for the first output value
    float loc3 = 0.3f * loc0 + 0.6f * loc1 + 0.1f * loc2;
    
    // Calculate auxiliary values for the remaining outputs
    float loc4 = loc0 - loc3;
    float loc5 = loc2 - loc3;
    float loc6 = loc5 / 2f;
    float loc7 = loc4 / 1.6f;
    
    // Assign computed values to arg1 array
    arg1[0] = loc3;
    arg1[1] = loc6;
    arg1[2] = loc7;
}
```

### Explanation:
1. **Clamping Values**: The function first ensures all input values (`arg0`) are within the range [0, 1] using `Math.max` and `Math.min`.
2. **Weighted Sum Calculation**: `loc3` is computed as a weighted combination of clamped input values.
3. **Auxiliary Calculations**: Intermediate results (`loc4`, `loc5`, `loc6`, `loc7`) are derived from the clamped inputs and the previously calculated `loc3`.
4. **Output Assignment**: The function updates the `arg1` array with the computed values.
